        <span class="pghdr">Unified Transportation Program (UTP) Process</span>
        <p>The Texas Transportation Commission has set five overall goals
          for the transportation system in our state:
        <ul>
          <li> Reliable Mobility</li>
          <li>              Improved Safety</li>
          <li>              Responsible Systems Preservation</li>
          <li>              Streamlined Project Delivery</li>
          <li>              Economic Vitality</li>
        </ul>        
		<p>To achieve these goals, TxDOT utilizes five strategies in its approach
          to the state transportation system. They five strategies are:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Plan It </li>
          <li>              Build It</li>
          <li>              Maintain It</li>
          <li> Use It</li>
          <li> Manage It</li>
        </ul>        
        <p> The UTP focuses on the Build It and Maintain It strategies.
          The UTP designates highway projects in each TxDOT district for the
          next 10 years. TxDOT publishes the UTP in two documents, the Statewide
          Mobility Program (SMP) and the Statewide Preservation Program (SPP).</p>
        <table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="10">
          <tr>
            <td><img src="../../../imglib/new/Build.It.jpg" width="75" height="75"></td>
            <td> The SMP addresses the Build It aspects of the UTP. The SMP includes 9 of the
 12 UTP funding categories related to highway construction on the state transportation
 system. Typical projects include: new road construction, road expansion projects
 such as adding a travel lane in each direction, air quality improvements,
 and projects or programs that help reduce air quality from the transportation
 system. All of the projects in the SMP are identified previously in transportation
 plans developed by the Metropolitan Planning Organization (MPO) in your city
 or region.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><img src="../../../imglib/new/Maintain.It.jpg" width="75" height="75"></td>
            <td> Projects in the SPP accounts for the Maintain It part of the
              program. The three funding categories in the SPP preserve your city
              or region's existing transportation system and protect your existing
              taxpayer investments. Projects in the SPP can include sealing or
              resurfacing of roads, traffic safety improvements, improved roadway signs and traffic markings,
              and maintenance of bridges. All of the projects in the SPP are
              identified previously in transportation plans developed by the
              Metropolitan Planning Organization (MPO) in your city or region.</td>
          </tr>
        </table>        
        <p><strong>PROJECT SELECTION PROCESS </strong></p>
        <p>The UTP is developed by the state to coordinate transportation construction
          and maintenance activities within and among the cities and areas of
          the state in the short-, medium- and long-term perspectives.</p>
        <p>Many transportation projects and programs in the UTP are selected
          after a thorough process of analysis and public discussion. It begins
          at the local level with you, the citizen, and your representatives
          on your MPO in coordination with technical experts, such as TxDOT district
          personnel. </p>
        <p>Needs and issues with your local transportation system can be more
          easily identified at the local level, by the people who use the system.
          Several drivers may notice the surface on their primary roadway deteriorating.
          The pavement may be wearing down forming grooves in the asphalt. Potholes
          may be much more noticeable. Traffic may be increasing to an inconvenient
          level for commuters on a main road. </p>
        <p>At the same time, TxDOT personnel in your district and in headquarters
          located in Austin collect and analyze data on various aspects of the
          local transportation system. This data is gathered on a regular basis
          by the department. These data include pavement quality, number of vehicles
          using the road system, accident rates, population growth, and projected
          growth in the city or region. </p>
        <p>Armed with data, analysis, and citizen input, the MPO of your region
          creates, approves, and publishes a short-range Transportation Improvement
          Program (TIP) for your area. The TIP represents the next 3 to 5 years
          and is part of the Metropolitan Transportation Plan (MTP) which covers
          your region's needs for the next 20 years. TIPs from all cities and
          regions within the state are combined to make the Statewide Transportation
          Improvement Program (STIP). MTPs are combined into the Statewide Transportation
          Plan (STP). Within these plans, some projects can be constructed relatively
          quickly, while major projects may take a decade or more to become a
          reality. Projects must be sequenced, or programmed, in a reasonable
          fashion that balances short, medium, and long term requirements for
          the transportation system. </p>
        <p>Both the MTP and STP contain more projects that can be reasonably
          afforded in any given ten year period. It is the nature of transportation
          planning and programming that desire outpaces funding. In this environment
          of limited funding the Texas Transportation Commission, TxDOT, and
          local agencies create the UTP. All parties strive for a program that
          balances the needs and desires of the cities and regions in the state.
          All parties strive for fairness. </p>
        <p><strong>PROJECT DEVELOPMENT PROCESS </strong></p>
        <p>Three levels of authority are used in developing a transportation
          project: PLAN, DEVELOP, and CONSTRUCT. </p>
        <p>PLAN projects are those mobility or high cost projects that require
          corridor studies, environmental impact statements, right of way acquisition.
          Big projects that take a very long time to complete are placed in this
          level of authority. PLAN projects are not included in the UTP since
          their construction is planned beyond the ten years contained in the
          UTP. </p>
        <p>DEVELOP status projects are included in the UTP. This level of authority
          allows TxDOT districts to prepare detailed construction plans and acquire
          the necessary right of way for the project. The plans are on the drawing
          boards and preparations are being made, but the machinery has yet to
          start work on the road. The number of DEVELOP status projects in the
          state is limited to seven years of anticipated future funding. </p>
        <p>CONSTRUCT status allows a TxDOT district to complete plans and award
        construction contracts for a project in the scheduled fiscal year. The
        work can now be performed on the roadway and citizens can see the effects
        of the project before, during, and after construction.</p>
        <p>For a more detailed overview of the UTP development process, click <a href="development.process.htm">here</a>.</p></td>
      </tr>
